      "SummaryText": "ntains the Emergency Response Plan) to help coordinate with local responders.\nAn Emergency Action Plan (EAP) that meets the requirements of the CCR Title 8 3220 is in place.\n\nEXTERNAL EVENTS ANALYSIS INFORMATION\nPursuant to the requirements of California Health & Safety Code, Title 19, Division 2, Chapter 4.5, 2745.7(q); the following external events analysis information was reviewed and submitted with the CalARP documentation: \n\u2022\tThe types of natural and human-caused external events considered in PHA Section 2760.2. \no\tDuring the PHA  a broad list of external events was considered by the Team. General events external to the plant that can conceivably cause a release of isopentane were addressed. The External Events that were considered are detailed within the PHA worksheets, which are included in the CalARP document.\n\u2022\tA seismic assessment of piping and equipment was performed in August 2022.\n \nPLANNED CHANGES TO IMPROVE SAFETY\nThe Process Hazard Analysis (PHA) study has been conducted to examine mitigation measures to improve safety at the facility. Planned changes to improve safety are listed as recommendations made during the revalidation of the PHA for Gould 2/Heber South, the development of the new PHA for OEC 1&2, and the performance of the Triennial Compliance Audit from this year.  Any outstanding recommendations will be addressed by December 2022."
    },
    {
      "ESSeqNum": 2,
      "FacilityID": 1000101011,
      "SummaryText": "se scenarios improbable. \nThere are numerous facility safeguards that serve to minimize the potential risks associated with an isopentane release, which include: \n\u2022\tAutomatic / Manual Shutdown Systems that enable remote isolation and depressurization of the processes and electrical isolation.\n\u2022\tAdequately Designed Pressure Relief System to provide a fail-safe backup to prevent over-pressurization\n\u2022\tPerimeter Fire Water Monitors and Storage Tank Deluge Systems to enable equipment cooling and prevent premature component failure.\n\u2022\tFlame and gas detection monitoring which interlocks with plant automatic shutdown systems and provides local audible and visual alarms.\nACCIDENTAL RELEASE PREVENTION PROGRAM\nAs part of the implementation of the accidental release prevention programs, prevention program elements are documented and implemented by the Heber facility to manage process safety issues associated with the use of isopentane. In addition, common industry standards, policies, and procedures are utilized to ensure safe practices are being performed.\nEach of the facility\u2019s three processes exceeds the 10,000 lb regulatory threshold quantity of isopentane.  As a result, all three processes are subject to CalARP Program Level 3, EPA RMP Program Level 3, and Cal/OSHA PSM.\nThe Prevention Program 3 elements include: \n\u2022\tProcess Safety Information\n\u2022\tProcess Hazard Analysis\n\u2022\tOperating Procedures\n\u2022\tTraining\n\u2022\tMechanical Integrity\n\u2022\tManagement of Change\n\u2022\tPre-Startup Safety Review\n\u2022\tCompliance Audits \n\u2022\tIncident Investigation \n\u2022\tEmployee Participation \n\u2022\tHot Work Permit\n\u2022\tContractors\nFIVE-YEAR ACCIDENT HISTORY\nThere have been no accidents meeting the Five-year Accident History criteria (per 40CFR68.42) at Heber 2. \nEMERGENCY RESPONSE PROGRAM \nHeber staff are not First Responders. Employees are trained to evacuate and call 911 in case of an emergency. Heber coordinates with the local Fire Department and First Responders. Heber has filed a Hazardous Materials Business Plan (which co"
    },
    {
      "ESSeqNum": 1,
      "FacilityID": 1000101011,
      "SummaryText": "cycle.  The electric power generated by this process is then sold to contracted off-takers. \nThere are a total of three processes in the facility; Gould 2 \u2013 commissioned in 2005, Heber South \u2013 commissioned in 2008, and a new OEC 1&2 I3LU \u2013 to be commissioned in the fourth quarter of 2022.  Six older, smaller process units known as Heber 2 are being decommissioned upon the startup of OEC 1&2 I3LU.  The maximum intended inventory of isopentane in all three processes is 826,992 lbs.  This includes the quantity charged to all three processes plus some residual quantity kept in storage.  The intent is to minimize the amount kept in storage to ensure adequate capacity for process evacuation during maintenance activity.\nThe site is currently operated by Heber staff and is staffed 24 hrs a day. The facility employs approximately 30 personnel.\nHAZARD ASSESSMENT SUMMARY/OFFSITE CONSEQUENCE ANALYSIS\nWorst-Case Release Scenario Results Summary\nScenario Description: The worst-case release scenario is defined by the release of the contents of the OEC 2 vaporizer.  A similar release from the OEC 1 vaporizer or any one of the five storage tanks (in full condition) would result in the same impact zone.  The potentially impacted public receptors are the adjacent agricultural land, the solar power facility, and an industrial concrete plant. The results can be found in the CalARP Submittal Binder.  \nAlternate Release Scenarios Results Summary\nScenario Description: An alternate release scenario was modeled as well.  Public receptors can also potentially be impacted by this release. The results can be found in the CalARP Submittal Binder.\nThe scenarios are also displayed in the graphic file attached to the RMP eSubmit document.\nRISK CONSIDERATIONS\nAlthough the use of isopentane has inherent potential risks, and worst-case and alternative-case release scenarios can potentially reach public receptors; Heber has recognized these potential risks and structured its safety programs to make the"
    },
