      "SummaryText": "ACCIDENTAL RELEASE PREVENTION POLICIES\nHeber has developed a risk management program and an emergency response plan for the Heber 2 facility to address the California Accidental Release Prevention (CalARP) Program requirements (California Code of Regulations, Title 19, Division 2, Chapter 4.5, \u00a72735-2785), the EPA Risk Management Program (40CFR68) and Cal/OSHA Process Safety Management (California Code of Regulations, Title 8, \u00a75189). Heber is extremely diligent in the handling of the regulated substance isopentane and is dedicated to the safety of its employees and the neighboring community. Heber staff are highly trained and utilizes modern equipment to monitor the facility and provide safeguards, while effectively and safely using isopentane for geothermal power production.\nHeber has a long-standing commitment to worker and public safety. This commitment is demonstrated by the resources invested in accident prevention, such as personnel training and consideration of safety in the design, operation, and maintenance of the isopentane systems. Heber\u2019s policy is to implement reasonable controls to prevent foreseeable releases of isopentane.\nSTATIONARY SOURCE AND REGULATED SUBSTANCE\nHeber\u2019s geothermal power production facility is fueled by hot geothermal brine from the Heber Geothermal Reservoir located in Heber, California, approximately 1.5 miles south of the town of Heber. The area around the facility consists of agricultural land, a solar power installation and an industrial concrete plant.\nThe process is a binary Rankine cycle. In that process, energy is transferred from the hot geothermal brine to an isopentane working fluid, referred to as motive fluid, in shell and tube heat exchangers.  The motive fluid is vaporized in the heat exchangers which drives turbines that are coupled to generators to produce electric power.  The motive fluid exiting the turbines is condensed in water-cooled shell and tube heat exchangers and returned to the process in a closed loop"
